{"title_page": "Southam", "text_new": "{{about|the town in Warwickshire}}\n{{Page numbers needed|date=May 2010}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|official_name= Southam\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.252|-1.39|display=inline,title}}\n|os_grid_reference= SP4161\n|label_position= bottom\n|static_image_name= Market Hill -Southam -Warwickshire.jpg\n|static_image_caption= Market Hill, Southam<br>([[:File:Market Hill -Southam -6Jan2005.jpg|click here for alternative view]])\n|population= 6,567\n|population_ref= ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])\n|civil_parish= Southam\n|shire_district= [[Stratford-on-Avon (district)|Stratford-on-Avon]]\n|shire_county= [[Warwickshire]]\n|region= West Midlands\n|country= England\n|constituency_westminster= [[Kenilworth and Southam (UK Parliament constituency)|Kenilworth and Southam]]\n|post_town= Southam\n|postcode_district= CV47\n|postcode_area= CV\n|dial_code= 01926\n|web= \n}}\n\n'''Southam''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|a\u028a|\u00f0|\u0259m}}) is a small market town and [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in the [[Stratford-on-Avon (district)|Stratford-on-Avon district]] of [[Warwickshire]], [[England]]. Southam is situated on the River Stowe (called 'The Brook' by many locals), which flows from [[Napton-on-the-Hill]] and joins Warwickshire's [[River Itchen, Warwickshire|River Itchen]] at [[Stoneythorpe]], just outside the town. The town is about {{convert|7+1/2|mi|0}} east of [[Leamington Spa]], about {{convert|10|mi}} from [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]] and [[Daventry]], {{convert|13|mi}} south of [[Coventry]] and {{convert|14|mi}} north of [[Banbury]].\n\nThe 2001 census recorded a parish population of 6,509,increasing to 6,567 at the 2011 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11128725&c=Southam&d=16&e=62&g=6472232&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1450880718748&enc=1|title=Town population 2011|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSoutham was a Royal [[Manorialism|manor]] until AD 998, when [[Ethelred the Unready]] granted it to [[Leofwine, Ealdorman of the Hwicce|Earl Leofwine]].{{sfn|Salzman|1951|pp=219\u2013226}} When [[St Mary's Priory and Cathedral#History|Coventry Priory]] was founded in 1043, Leofwine's son [[Leofric, Earl of Mercia]] granted Southam to it.{{sfn|Salzman|1951|pp=219\u2013226}} The [[Domesday Book]] records the manor as \"''Sucham''\".{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}} The Priory, which in the 12th century became the first [[Coventry Cathedral]], kept Southam until the 16th century when it surrendered all its estates to [[the Crown]] in the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]].{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}}  The current Manor House is Grade II * listed and dates from the early 17th century.\n\nThe present [[Church of England parish church|parish church]] of St James was built in the 14th century.{{sfn|Salzman|1951|pp=219\u2013226}}{{sfn|Pevsner|Wedgwood|1966|p=403}}<ref name=EH-church>{{NHLE |num= 1185823 |desc=Church of St James |accessdate=19 October 2012}}</ref> In the 15th century the spire was added{{sfn|Pevsner|Wedgwood|1966|p=403}} and the [[chancel]] was rebuilt.<ref name=EH-church/> The [[nave]]'s [[clerestory]] and present roof were added in the 16th century, along with the present west door.<ref name=EH-church/> St James' is a [[Listed building#Categories of listed building|Grade I listed building]].<ref name=EH-church/>\n\nIn the [[medieval]] era the town minted its own [[local currency]]{{citation needed|date=June 2009}} because local people found regular English currency too high in value for everyday use. In the [[English Civil War]] [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] used Southam's mint to make new coins to pay his troops. The building is early 16th century<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1035589 |desc=The Old Mint Public House, Coventry Road |accessdate=19 October 2012}}</ref> and is now the Old Mint [[public house]].{{sfn|Pevsner|Wedgwood|1966|p=403}}\n\nSoutham's Holy Well, in the picturesque Stowe river valley, is a Grade II listed building and scheduled Ancient Monument, and was first recorded in the year 998.<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://people.bath.ac.uk/liskmj/living-spring/sourcearchive/fs6/fs6pat1.htm |last1=Patchell |first1=P.M. |last2=Patchell |first2=E.M. |editor-last=Jordan |editor-first=Kathy |date=Winter 1986 |volume=6 |title=The Wells of Old Warwickshire |journal=Living Spring Journal |publisher=[[University of Bath]] |accessdate=15 March 2012}}</ref> The Well was used in medieval times by local monks and for hundreds of years as the town's principal water supply. Water from a natural mineral spring feeds the semi-circular Well and pours through the mouths of carved stone gargoyles into the river. The water from the Well was said to cure eye complaints.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} The Holy Well and paths were renovated in 2007 using a National Lottery grant including wheelchair access and oak seats designed by artist Will Glanfield as part of his Southam Stories project, and fall within the unspoilt Stowe valley Area of Restraint as a protected landscape of special significance and value to the town.\n\nIn the 1540s [[John Leland (antiquary)|John Leland]] visited the town and described it as ''\"a modest market town of a single street\"''.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}} [[William Shakespeare]] mentions Southam in ''[[Henry VI, part 3]]'', Act V, Scene I, Lines 10\u201316:\n\n<blockquote>\n''WARWICK''<br/>\n    Say, Somerville, what says my loving son?<br/>\n    And, by thy guess, how nigh is Clarence now?<br/>\n<br/>\n''SOMERSET''<br/>\n    At Southam I did leave him with his forces,<br/>\n    And do expect him here some two hours hence.<br/>\n<br/>\n''WARWICK''<br/>\n    Then Clarence is at hand, I hear his drum.<br/>\n<br/>\n''SOMERSET''<br/>\n    It is not his, my lord; here Southam lies:<br/>\n    The drum your honour hears marcheth from Warwick.<br/>\n</blockquote>\n\nCharles I passed through Southam just before the outbreak of the Civil War and apparently was not made welcome by the townsfolk, who refused to ring the parish church bells.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}} On 23 August 1642, the day after King Charles 1st formally declared war on Parliament, a skirmish was fought outside the town between [[Roundhead|Parliamentary]] forces led by [[Robert Greville, 2nd Baron Brooke|Lord Brooke]] and [[Cavalier|Royalist]] forces commanded by the [[Spencer Compton, 2nd Earl of Northampton|Earl of Northampton]]. The Battle of Southam is claimed by locals to have been the first battle of the English Civil Wars.  Later that year, Charles stayed in Southam before the [[Battle of Edgehill]] on 23 October 1642.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}} In 1645 [[Oliver Cromwell]] and 7,000 Parliamentary troops stayed in the town.<ref>{{cite book |author=Warwickshire Federation of [[Women's Institute]]s |year=2000 |title=The Warwickshire Village Book |location=Newbury |publisher=Countryside Books |isbn=1-85306-652-4 |page=}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[stagecoach]] era Southam became an important stop {{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} on the coach road between Coventry and [[Oxford]]. Many old [[coaching inn]]s remain in the town.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}} However, few buildings in Southam date from before 1741, when a large fire devastated the town.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}}\n\nSoutham was never on a [[railway]]. The [[Great Western Railway]] had absorbed the [[Birmingham and Oxford Junction Railway]] in 1848, and when the GWR line to Birmingham opened in 1852 Southam had a station {{convert|3|mi|0}} to the south-west, named {{rws|Southam Road and Harbury}}. [[British Rail]]ways (BR) closed the station to goods in 1963 and passengers in 1964. The line is now part of the London Marylebone to Birmingham [[Chiltern Line]].\n\nThe [[London and North Western Railway]] completed its [[Weedon to Marton Junction Line]] in 1895 and opened {{rws|Southam and Long Itchington}} station on it {{convert|2|mi|0}} north of Southam. British Railways closed the station to passengers in 1958 and goods in 1965.\n\nSoutham was the seat of [[Southam Rural District]] from 1894 until 1974, when under the [[Local Government Act 1972]] it was made part of [[Stratford-on-Avon (district)|Stratford-on-Avon District]].\n\nSoutham was in the [[parliamentary constituency]] of [[Stratford-on-Avon (UK Parliament constituency)|Stratford-on-Avon]] until the [[Boundary changes for the 2010 United Kingdom general election|boundary changes]] approved by Parliament in June 2007 when it became part of the new constituency of [[Kenilworth and Southam (UK Parliament constituency)|Kenilworth and Southam]]. The constituency was first contested in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election]].\n\n[[RAF Southam]], about {{convert|0.6|mi|0}} east of the town, was a [[World War II]] airfield. It was opened in 1940 and closed at the end of 1944. It was a training base and a relief landing ground.\n\nSoutham's history is commemorated in [[Southam's Cardall Collection]].\n\n===Historic population===\n{|  class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year!!Population\n|-\n|1801 || align=\"right\"| 900{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n|-\n|1911 || align=\"right\"| 1,804{{sfn|Salzman|1951|pp=219\u2013226}}\n|-\n|1971 || align=\"right\"| 4,435{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n|-\n|1991 || align=\"right\"| 5,304{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n|-\n|2001 || align=\"right\"| 6,509<ref name=ONS>{{cite web |url= http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do;jsessionid=ac1f930cce6fdd7c07e970544ee913cff5743b9a59c.e38Qa3mPbh4Kai0Lb34Na3uRbx0Re6fznA5Pp7ftolbGmkTy?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790540&bhjs=0 |title=Area selected: Stratford-on-Avon (Non-Metropolitan District) |work=Neighbourhood Statistics |publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]] |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|2011 || align=\"right\"| 6,499{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n|}\n\n==Economy==\nThe dominant rock type for the area is [[Blue Lias]] clay. Until recently<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cementkilns.co.uk/cement_kiln_southam.html|title=cementkilns.co.uk|accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref> there was a cement factory and associated [[quarry]] {{convert|1|mi}} north of the town. The works was served by both rail and canal transport&nbsp;\u2014 the latter being a short arm from the [[Grand Union Canal]]. Cement production was relocated to Rugby in the late 1990s but quarrying at the site continues.\n\nSouth of the town is an [[industrial estate]] that is a significant source of local employment. Europe's largest privately owned computer games company, [[Codemasters]], was founded by two locals and is based nearby.  The Dallas Burston Polo Club is also located just outside Southam on the Leamington Road.\n\nSoutham has become a commuter town due to its road links and location. Taxi and minicab firms operate in the area and frequent bus services serve Southam and local villages.\n\n==Facilities==\n===Education===\nSoutham has three [[primary school]]s and a [[secondary school]] ([[Southam College]]) with 1,643 students on roll from Southam and local villages. There is a leisure centre with swimming pool and gym next to the College on Welsh Road West.\n\n===Shopping===\nThe main shopping street runs through the centre of town. Each Tuesday there is a small but popular market on Market Hill. There is a range of shops in the town centre, including a [[Heart of England Co-operative Society|Co-Op]] supermarket, a post office, an optician, a pharmacy, W Goodwin & Sons hardware store and undertaker, a carpet shop, the Southam Office Supplies stationery and print shop, a dry cleaner and laundry, two florists, one ladies clothing shop, other small speciality and gift shops, Acorns Hospice and The Myton Hospices charity shops, and a branch of Lloyds Bank. In spring 2013 a branch of [[The Original Factory Shop]] opened on Oxford Street following the closure of Budgens Supermarket.  A Tesco supermarket is located on the outskirts of town, on the Kineton Road industrial estate.\n\n===Other===\nThe town's pubs include the Black Dog, the Bowling Green, The Crown, the Old Mint and the Millstone Hare, part of the Dallas Burston Polo Club. There is also a [[Working Men's Club and Institute Union|CIU]]-affiliated Sports and Social Club in School Street. Southam town centre also has several cafes, various takeaway food outlets, a public library and information centre, several hairdressers, a beautician, two dental surgeries, a chiropodist, a bookmaker, a saddlery and professional services including solicitors, estate agents, accountants and financial advisers. The main car park in Wood Street is free of charge, and has public lavatories.\n\nSoutham also has a [http://www.southamfirestation.com Retained Fire Station]. The police station is now closed to the general public; for non-emergency police enquiries, people should go to the public library. The main entertainment venue in the town is Grange Hall in Coventry Street, which hosts dramatic and musical performances, meetings and dance/exercise classes. The Graham Adams Centre in St James Road houses the Grange Pre-school, the Youth Club and a community cafe. It is also home to adult education classes and is a meeting place for many of the town's youth and community groups.\n\n===Religion===\nThere are four churches in Southam. St James's parish church is behind Market Hill. Both Our Lady and St Wulstan's Catholic church and the Congregational chapel are on Wood Street, and the Community Church is on Coventry Street. There is also a small but active [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in England|Bah\u00e1\u00b4\u00ed]] group in the town{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}. The footpath from St James church along the protected Stowe valley to the historic Holy Well and on to Stoneythorpe Hall is a popular route for local people, ornithologists and other naturalists.\n\n===Sport and recreation===\n[http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/southam/ Southam Rugby Club] was formed in 1962. In 1969 the club purchased pitches at Kineton Road and started playing home games. Over three years' money was raised to build the club house which was constructed mainly by the players and was opened in 1972. Today the club plays in the Midland League and has three senior teams and a colts team.\n\n[[Southam United F.C.]] is the town's football club, and Southam also has a bowling club, a cricket club and the six pitch [[Dallas Burston Polo Club]] which includes conference and events facilities and the Millstone Hare pub and restaurant.\n\nSoutham is home to 2028 (Southam) Squadron Air Training Corps, an RAF-sponsored ([[Royal Air Force]]) youth organisation for 13- to 20-year-olds. The squadron is based in Millar House, Wattons Lane.\n\n===Parks===\nSoutham's recreational ground, locally known simply as 'the Rec', is located on Park Lane; the land adjoins St James' churchyard which itself extends to Park Lane, the lower part of Market Hill and the upper part of Warwick Street. The bottom of the park is a bare field used mainly for ball games and the upper part contains various kinds of play equipment, with a separate area for very young children. The second largest park is at Tollgate Road, locally referred to as 'Tollgate'.\n\n==Transport==\n\nSoutham is between Leamington Spa and Daventry on the [[A425 road]] and between Coventry and Banbury on the [[A423 road]]. The [[A426 road]] connects it to Rugby. Southam is about {{convert|15|mi}} from [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], birthplace of [[William Shakespeare]]. About {{convert|8|mi}} from Southam is the [[M40 motorway]], though the town is surprisingly not indicated.\n\nThe nearest railway stations are {{rws|Leamington Spa}}, {{rws|Rugby}} and {{rws|Banbury}}.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{alumni|residents|date=October 2018}}\n*[[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]] [[Charles Walter Allfrey|Sir Charles Allfrey]], [[British Army]] commander, veteran of [[World War I]] and [[World War II]].\n*[[Steve Beaton]], 1996 [[World Professional Darts Championship|World Professional Darts Champion]].\n*[[Arthur Cox (footballer)|Arthur Cox]], who managed [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] and [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] football clubs between 1980 and 1993, was born at Southam in December 1939.\n*[[Flight Lieutenant]] [[Jon Egging]], former Air Cadet at 2028 Squadron [[Air Training Corps]], [[Red Arrows]] display team pilot during 2009 and 2011 seasons.\n*[[Trina Gulliver]], nine times women's World Professional Darts Champion, who moved to [[Somerset]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/news/Golden-Girl-hits-bullseye/article-1716657-detail/article.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130114045504/http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/news/Golden-Girl-hits-bullseye/article-1716657-detail/article.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 January 2013 |title=Golden Girl hits bullseye |publisher=ThisIsSomerset.co.uk |date=15 January 2010 |accessdate=8 January 2011 }}</ref>\n*[[Henry Lilley Smith]] (1787/88 \u2013 1859) founded a [[cottage hospital]], Southam Dispensary, in 1823.{{sfn|Salzman|1951|pp=219\u2013226}}\n*[[Steve Walwyn]], guitarist with [[Dr. Feelgood (band)|Dr. Feelgood]], was born in Southam in 1956.\n*[[Adam Woodyatt]], ''[[EastEnders]]'' actor, had a home in Southam for many years.\n*Richard and [[David Darling (entrepreneur)|David Darling]], aka [[Codemasters]], award-winning videogames developer company, founded in 1986 and retains its head office of several hundred employees in Southam.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |last=Allen |first=Geoff |year=2000 |title=Warwickshire Towns and Villages |location=Ammanford |publisher=Sigma Leisure |isbn=1-85058-642-X |pages=not cited |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Pevsner |first1=Nikolaus |author1-link=Nikolaus Pevsner |last2=Wedgwood |first2=Alexandra |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |title=Warwickshire |year=1966 |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=Harmondsworth |isbn= |page=403 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Salzman |editor-first=L.F. |editor-link=Louis Francis Salzman |series=[[Victoria County History]] |title=A History of the County of Warwick, Volume 6: Knightlow hundred |year=1951 |publisher= |location= |pages=219\u2013226 |url= http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=57133 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- PLEASE SEE [[WP:ELNO]] BEFORE ADDING LINKS-->\n{{Commons category|Southam, Warwickshire|Southam}}\n*[[wikisource:The Third Part of King Henry the Sixth#SCENE I. Coventry. Wikisource: William Shakespeare|Wikisource&nbsp;\u2013 ''The Third Part of King Henry the Sixth''&nbsp;\u2013 Act V, Scene I]] \u2013 contains mentions of Southam.\n\n{{Stratford-on-Avon district}}\n{{Warwickshire}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Southam| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Warwickshire]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Warwickshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Warwickshire]]\n[[Category:Holy wells in England]]\n[[Category:Stratford-on-Avon District]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the town in Warwickshire}}\n{{Page numbers needed|date=May 2010}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|official_name= Southam\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.252|-1.39|display=inline,title}}\n|os_grid_reference= SP4161\n|label_position= bottom\n|static_image_name= Market Hill -Southam -Warwickshire.jpg\n|static_image_caption= Market Hill, Southam<br>([[:File:Market Hill -Southam -6Jan2005.jpg|click here for alternative view]])\n|population= 6,567\n|population_ref= ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])\n|civil_parish= Southam\n|shire_district= [[Stratford-on-Avon (district)|Stratford-on-Avon]]\n|shire_county= [[Warwickshire]]\n|region= West Midlands\n|country= England\n|constituency_westminster= [[Kenilworth and Southam (UK Parliament constituency)|Kenilworth and Southam]]\n|post_town= Southam\n|postcode_district= CV47\n|postcode_area= CV\n|dial_code= 01926\n|web= \n}}\n\n'''Southam''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|a\u028a|\u00f0|\u0259m}}) is a small market tow and [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in the [[Stratford-on-Avon (district)|Stratford-on-Avon district]] of [[Warwickshire]], [[England]]. Southam is situated on the River Stowe (called 'The Brook' by many locals), which flows from [[Napton-on-the-Hill]] and joins Warwickshire's [[River Itchen, Warwickshire|River Itchen]] at [[Stoneythorpe]], just outside the town. The town is about {{convert|7+1/2|mi|0}} east of [[Leamington Spa]], about {{convert|10|mi}} from [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]] and [[Daventry]], {{convert|13|mi}} south of [[Coventry]] and {{convert|14|mi}} north of [[Banbury]].\n\nThe 2001 census recorded a parish population of 6,509,increasing to 6,567 at the 2011 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11128725&c=Southam&d=16&e=62&g=6472232&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1450880718748&enc=1|title=Town population 2011|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSoutham was a Royal [[Manorialism|manor]] until AD 998, when [[Ethelred the Unready]] granted it to [[Leofwine, Ealdorman of the Hwicce|Earl Leofwine]].{{sfn|Salzman|1951|pp=219\u2013226}} When [[St Mary's Priory and Cathedral#History|Coventry Priory]] was founded in 1043, Leofwine's son [[Leofric, Earl of Mercia]] granted Southam to it.{{sfn|Salzman|1951|pp=219\u2013226}} The [[Domesday Book]] records the manor as \"''Sucham''\".{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}} The Priory, which in the 12th century became the first [[Coventry Cathedral]], kept Southam until the 16th century when it surrendered all its estates to [[the Crown]] in the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]].{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}}  The current Manor House is Grade II * listed and dates from the early 17th century.\n\nThe present [[Church of England parish church|parish church]] of St James was built in the 14th century.{{sfn|Salzman|1951|pp=219\u2013226}}{{sfn|Pevsner|Wedgwood|1966|p=403}}<ref name=EH-church>{{NHLE |num= 1185823 |desc=Church of St James |accessdate=19 October 2012}}</ref> In the 15th century the spire was added{{sfn|Pevsner|Wedgwood|1966|p=403}} and the [[chancel]] was rebuilt.<ref name=EH-church/> The [[nave]]'s [[clerestory]] and present roof were added in the 16th century, along with the present west door.<ref name=EH-church/> St James' is a [[Listed building#Categories of listed building|Grade I listed building]].<ref name=EH-church/>\n\nIn the [[medieval]] era the town minted its own [[local currency]]{{citation needed|date=June 2009}} because local people found regular English currency too high in value for everyday use. In the [[English Civil War]] [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] used Southam's mint to make new coins to pay his troops. The building is early 16th century<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1035589 |desc=The Old Mint Public House, Coventry Road |accessdate=19 October 2012}}</ref> and is now the Old Mint [[public house]].{{sfn|Pevsner|Wedgwood|1966|p=403}}\n\nSoutham's Holy Well, in the picturesque Stowe river valley, is a Grade II listed building and scheduled Ancient Monument, and was first recorded in the year 998.<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://people.bath.ac.uk/liskmj/living-spring/sourcearchive/fs6/fs6pat1.htm |last1=Patchell |first1=P.M. |last2=Patchell |first2=E.M. |editor-last=Jordan |editor-first=Kathy |date=Winter 1986 |volume=6 |title=The Wells of Old Warwickshire |journal=Living Spring Journal |publisher=[[University of Bath]] |accessdate=15 March 2012}}</ref> The Well was used in medieval times by local monks and for hundreds of years as the town's principal water supply. Water from a natural mineral spring feeds the semi-circular Well and pours through the mouths of carved stone gargoyles into the river. The water from the Well was said to cure eye complaints.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} The Holy Well and paths were renovated in 2007 using a National Lottery grant including wheelchair access and oak seats designed by artist Will Glanfield as part of his Southam Stories project, and fall within the unspoilt Stowe valley Area of Restraint as a protected landscape of special significance and value to the town.\n\nIn the 1540s [[John Leland (antiquary)|John Leland]] visited the town and described it as ''\"a modest market town of a single street\"''.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}} [[William Shakespeare]] mentions Southam in ''[[Henry VI, part 3]]'', Act V, Scene I, Lines 10\u201316:\n\n<blockquote>\n''WARWICK''<br/>\n    Say, Somerville, what says my loving son?<br/>\n    And, by thy guess, how nigh is Clarence now?<br/>\n<br/>\n''SOMERSET''<br/>\n    At Southam I did leave him with his forces,<br/>\n    And do expect him here some two hours hence.<br/>\n<br/>\n''WARWICK''<br/>\n    Then Clarence is at hand, I hear his drum.<br/>\n<br/>\n''SOMERSET''<br/>\n    It is not his, my lord; here Southam lies:<br/>\n    The drum your honour hears marcheth from Warwick.<br/>\n</blockquote>\n\nCharles I passed through Southam just before the outbreak of the Civil War and apparently was not made welcome by the townsfolk, who refused to ring the parish church bells.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}} On 23 August 1642, the day after King Charles 1st formally declared war on Parliament, a skirmish was fought outside the town between [[Roundhead|Parliamentary]] forces led by [[Robert Greville, 2nd Baron Brooke|Lord Brooke]] and [[Cavalier|Royalist]] forces commanded by the [[Spencer Compton, 2nd Earl of Northampton|Earl of Northampton]]. The Battle of Southam is claimed by locals to have been the first battle of the English Civil Wars.  Later that year, Charles stayed in Southam before the [[Battle of Edgehill]] on 23 October 1642.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}} In 1645 [[Oliver Cromwell]] and 7,000 Parliamentary troops stayed in the town.<ref>{{cite book |author=Warwickshire Federation of [[Women's Institute]]s |year=2000 |title=The Warwickshire Village Book |location=Newbury |publisher=Countryside Books |isbn=1-85306-652-4 |page=}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[stagecoach]] era Southam became an important stop {{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} on the coach road between Coventry and [[Oxford]]. Many old [[coaching inn]]s remain in the town.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}} However, few buildings in Southam date from before 1741, when a large fire devastated the town.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=not cited}}\n\nSoutham was never on a [[railway]]. The [[Great Western Railway]] had absorbed the [[Birmingham and Oxford Junction Railway]] in 1848, and when the GWR line to Birmingham opened in 1852 Southam had a station {{convert|3|mi|0}} to the south-west, named {{rws|Southam Road and Harbury}}. [[British Rail]]ways (BR) closed the station to goods in 1963 and passengers in 1964. The line is now part of the London Marylebone to Birmingham [[Chiltern Line]].\n\nThe [[London and North Western Railway]] completed its [[Weedon to Marton Junction Line]] in 1895 and opened {{rws|Southam and Long Itchington}} station on it {{convert|2|mi|0}} north of Southam. British Railways closed the station to passengers in 1958 and goods in 1965.\n\nSoutham was the seat of [[Southam Rural District]] from 1894 until 1974, when under the [[Local Government Act 1972]] it was made part of [[Stratford-on-Avon (district)|Stratford-on-Avon District]].\n\nSoutham was in the [[parliamentary constituency]] of [[Stratford-on-Avon (UK Parliament constituency)|Stratford-on-Avon]] until the [[Boundary changes for the 2010 United Kingdom general election|boundary changes]] approved by Parliament in June 2007 when it became part of the new constituency of [[Kenilworth and Southam (UK Parliament constituency)|Kenilworth and Southam]]. The constituency was first contested in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election]].\n\n[[RAF Southam]], about {{convert|0.6|mi|0}} east of the town, was a [[World War II]] airfield. It was opened in 1940 and closed at the end of 1944. It was a training base and a relief landing ground.\n\nSoutham's history is commemorated in [[Southam's Cardall Collection]].\n\n===Historic population===\n{|  class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year!!Population\n|-\n|1801 || align=\"right\"| 900{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n|-\n|1911 || align=\"right\"| 1,804{{sfn|Salzman|1951|pp=219\u2013226}}\n|-\n|1971 || align=\"right\"| 4,435{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n|-\n|1991 || align=\"right\"| 5,304{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n|-\n|2001 || align=\"right\"| 6,509<ref name=ONS>{{cite web |url= http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do;jsessionid=ac1f930cce6fdd7c07e970544ee913cff5743b9a59c.e38Qa3mPbh4Kai0Lb34Na3uRbx0Re6fznA5Pp7ftolbGmkTy?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790540&bhjs=0 |title=Area selected: Stratford-on-Avon (Non-Metropolitan District) |work=Neighbourhood Statistics |publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]] |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|2011 || align=\"right\"| 6,499{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n|}\n\n==Economy==\nThe dominant rock type for the area is [[Blue Lias]] clay. Until recently<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cementkilns.co.uk/cement_kiln_southam.html|title=cementkilns.co.uk|accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref> there was a cement factory and associated [[quarry]] {{convert|1|mi}} north of the town. The works was served by both rail and canal transport&nbsp;\u2014 the latter being a short arm from the [[Grand Union Canal]]. Cement production was relocated to Rugby in the late 1990s but quarrying at the site continues.\n\nSouth of the town is an [[industrial estate]] that is a significant source of local employment. Europe's largest privately owned computer games company, [[Codemasters]], was founded by two locals and is based nearby.  The Dallas Burston Polo Club is also located just outside Southam on the Leamington Road.\n\nSoutham has become a commuter town due to its road links and location. Taxi and minicab firms operate in the area and frequent bus services serve Southam and local villages.\n\n==Facilities==\n===Education===\nSoutham has three [[primary school]]s and a [[secondary school]] ([[Southam College]]) with 1,643 students on roll from Southam and local villages. There is a leisure centre with swimming pool and gym next to the College on Welsh Road West.\n\n===Shopping===\nThe main shopping street runs through the centre of town. Each Tuesday there is a small but popular market on Market Hill. There is a range of shops in the town centre, including a [[Heart of England Co-operative Society|Co-Op]] supermarket, a post office, an optician, a pharmacy, W Goodwin & Sons hardware store and undertaker, a carpet shop, the Southam Office Supplies stationery and print shop, a dry cleaner and laundry, two florists, one ladies clothing shop, other small speciality and gift shops, Acorns Hospice and The Myton Hospices charity shops, and a branch of Lloyds Bank. In spring 2013 a branch of [[The Original Factory Shop]] opened on Oxford Street following the closure of Budgens Supermarket.  A Tesco supermarket is located on the outskirts of town, on the Kineton Road industrial estate.\n\n===Other===\nThe town's pubs include the Black Dog, the Bowling Green, The Crown, the Old Mint and the Millstone Hare, part of the Dallas Burston Polo Club. There is also a [[Working Men's Club and Institute Union|CIU]]-affiliated Sports and Social Club in School Street. Southam town centre also has several cafes, various takeaway food outlets, a public library and information centre, several hairdressers, a beautician, two dental surgeries, a chiropodist, a bookmaker, a saddlery and professional services including solicitors, estate agents, accountants and financial advisers. The main car park in Wood Street is free of charge, and has public lavatories.\n\nSoutham also has a [http://www.southamfirestation.com Retained Fire Station]. The police station is now closed to the general public; for non-emergency police enquiries, people should go to the public library. The main entertainment venue in the town is Grange Hall in Coventry Street, which hosts dramatic and musical performances, meetings and dance/exercise classes. The Graham Adams Centre in St James Road houses the Grange Pre-school, the Youth Club and a community cafe. It is also home to adult education classes and is a meeting place for many of the town's youth and community groups.\n\n===Religion===\nThere are four churches in Southam. St James's parish church is behind Market Hill. Both Our Lady and St Wulstan's Catholic church and the Congregational chapel are on Wood Street, and the Community Church is on Coventry Street. There is also a small but active [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in England|Bah\u00e1\u00b4\u00ed]] group in the town{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}. The footpath from St James church along the protected Stowe valley to the historic Holy Well and on to Stoneythorpe Hall is a popular route for local people, ornithologists and other naturalists.\n\n===Sport and recreation===\n[http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/southam/ Southam Rugby Club] was formed in 1962. In 1969 the club purchased pitches at Kineton Road and started playing home games. Over three years' money was raised to build the club house which was constructed mainly by the players and was opened in 1972. Today the club plays in the Midland League and has three senior teams and a colts team.\n\n[[Southam United F.C.]] is the town's football club, and Southam also has a bowling club, a cricket club and the six pitch [[Dallas Burston Polo Club]] which includes conference and events facilities and the Millstone Hare pub and restaurant.\n\nSoutham is home to 2028 (Southam) Squadron Air Training Corps, an RAF-sponsored ([[Royal Air Force]]) youth organisation for 13- to 20-year-olds. The squadron is based in Millar House, Wattons Lane.\n\n===Parks===\nSoutham's recreational ground, locally known simply as 'the Rec', is located on Park Lane; the land adjoins St James' churchyard which itself extends to Park Lane, the lower part of Market Hill and the upper part of Warwick Street. The bottom of the park is a bare field used mainly for ball games and the upper part contains various kinds of play equipment, with a separate area for very young children. The second largest park is at Tollgate Road, locally referred to as 'Tollgate'.\n\n==Transport==\n\nSoutham is between Leamington Spa and Daventry on the [[A425 road]] and between Coventry and Banbury on the [[A423 road]]. The [[A426 road]] connects it to Rugby. Southam is about {{convert|15|mi}} from [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], birthplace of [[William Shakespeare]]. About {{convert|8|mi}} from Southam is the [[M40 motorway]], though the town is surprisingly not indicated.\n\nThe nearest railway stations are {{rws|Leamington Spa}}, {{rws|Rugby}} and {{rws|Banbury}}.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{alumni|residents|date=October 2018}}\n*[[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]] [[Charles Walter Allfrey|Sir Charles Allfrey]], [[British Army]] commander, veteran of [[World War I]] and [[World War II]].\n*[[Steve Beaton]], 1996 [[World Professional Darts Championship|World Professional Darts Champion]].\n*[[Arthur Cox (footballer)|Arthur Cox]], who managed [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] and [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] football clubs between 1980 and 1993, was born at Southam in December 1939.\n*[[Flight Lieutenant]] [[Jon Egging]], former Air Cadet at 2028 Squadron [[Air Training Corps]], [[Red Arrows]] display team pilot during 2009 and 2011 seasons.\n*[[Trina Gulliver]], nine times women's World Professional Darts Champion, who moved to [[Somerset]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/news/Golden-Girl-hits-bullseye/article-1716657-detail/article.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130114045504/http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/news/Golden-Girl-hits-bullseye/article-1716657-detail/article.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 January 2013 |title=Golden Girl hits bullseye |publisher=ThisIsSomerset.co.uk |date=15 January 2010 |accessdate=8 January 2011 }}</ref>\n*[[Henry Lilley Smith]] (1787/88 \u2013 1859) founded a [[cottage hospital]], Southam Dispensary, in 1823.{{sfn|Salzman|1951|pp=219\u2013226}}\n*[[Steve Walwyn]], guitarist with [[Dr. Feelgood (band)|Dr. Feelgood]], was born in Southam in 1956.\n*[[Adam Woodyatt]], ''[[EastEnders]]'' actor, had a home in Southam for many years.\n*Richard and [[David Darling (entrepreneur)|David Darling]], aka [[Codemasters]], award-winning videogames developer company, founded in 1986 and retains its head office of several hundred employees in Southam.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |last=Allen |first=Geoff |year=2000 |title=Warwickshire Towns and Villages |location=Ammanford |publisher=Sigma Leisure |isbn=1-85058-642-X |pages=not cited |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Pevsner |first1=Nikolaus |author1-link=Nikolaus Pevsner |last2=Wedgwood |first2=Alexandra |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |title=Warwickshire |year=1966 |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=Harmondsworth |isbn= |page=403 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Salzman |editor-first=L.F. |editor-link=Louis Francis Salzman |series=[[Victoria County History]] |title=A History of the County of Warwick, Volume 6: Knightlow hundred |year=1951 |publisher= |location= |pages=219\u2013226 |url= http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=57133 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- PLEASE SEE [[WP:ELNO]] BEFORE ADDING LINKS-->\n{{Commons category|Southam, Warwickshire|Southam}}\n*[[wikisource:The Third Part of King Henry the Sixth#SCENE I. Coventry. Wikisource: William Shakespeare|Wikisource&nbsp;\u2013 ''The Third Part o