{"title_page": "2012 Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council election", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n\n[[File:Calderdale UK ward map 2012 Election.svg|thumb|right|300px|2012 local election results in Calderdale]]\n\nThe '''2012 Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council election''' took place on 3 May 2012 to elect members of [[Calderdale Metropolitan Borough Council]] in [[West Yorkshire]], [[England]].<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-17299200 |title=Local elections 2012 |accessdate=2012-04-30 |work=BBC News}}</ref> This was on the same day as other [[2012 United Kingdom local elections]]. After the election the council continued to have [[no overall control]] and continue to be run by a coalition between the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].\n\nThe Warley Councillor Keith Hutson stepped down in 2012 due to health reasons. A by-election was held on 19 July 2012. The seat was held by the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] with James Baker winning the seat.<ref>[http://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/calderdale/lib-dems-hold-on-in-warley-by-election-1-4757746 Lib-Dems hold on in Warley by-election]. ''Halifax Courier''. Retrieved 2 August 2016.</ref>\n\nIn this year Councillor Nader Fekri for Calder ward defected to [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] from the Liberal Democrats in 2012 saying that he could no longer support the coalition in the national parliament with the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]].<ref>[http://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/calderdale/update-nader-fekri-s-resignation-letter-1-4842404 Nader Fekri\u2019s resignation letter]. ''Halifax Courier''. Retrieved 2 August 2016.</ref>\n\nIn April 2013 the coalition between Labour and the Liberal Democrats collapsed as Labour pulled out over disagreements over benefit cuts.<ref>[http://www.examiner.co.uk/news/west-yorkshire-news/coaltion-deal-run-calderdale-council-4929992 Coalition deal to run Calderdale Council is ended by Labour group]. ''Huddersfield Examiner''. Retrieved 18 August 2017.</ref> Labour continued to run the council as a minority administration.<ref>[http://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/news/politics/council-s-new-way-is-fairer-1-5639957 Council\u2019s new way is \u2018fairer\u2019]. ''Halifax Courier''. Retrieved 18 August 2017.</ref>\n\n==Council composition==\n'''Prior to''' the election the composition of the council was:\n{| style=\"width:100%; text-align:center;\"\n|+ \u2193\n|- style=\"color:white;\"\n| style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}; width:25.49%;\" | '''13'''\n| style=\"background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; width:41.18%;\" | '''21'''\n| style=\"background:{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}; width:25.49%;\" | '''13'''\n| style=\"background:{{Independent Liberal Democrat/meta/color}}; width:1.96%;\" | '''1'''\n| style=\"background:{{Independent (politician)/meta/color}}; width:5.88%;\" | '''3'''\n|-\n| <span style=\"color:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};\">'''Labour'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}};\">'''Conservative'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}};\">'''Lib Dem'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:{{Independent Liberal Democrat/meta/color}};\">'''ILD'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:{{Independent (politician)/meta/color}};\">'''Ind'''</span>\n|}\n\n'''After''' the election the composition of the council was:\n{| style=\"width:100%; text-align:center;\"\n|+ \u2193\n|- style=\"color:white;\"\n| style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}; width:39.22%;\" | '''20'''\n| style=\"background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; width:33.33%;\" | '''17'''\n| style=\"background:{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}; width:23.53%;\" | '''12'''\n| style=\"background:{{Independent (politician)/meta/color}}; width:3.92%;\" | '''2'''\n|-\n| <span style=\"color:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};\">'''Labour'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}};\">'''Conservative'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}};\">'''Lib Dem'''</span>\n| <span style=\"color:{{Independent (politician)/meta/color}};\">'''Ind'''</span>\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! valign=centre colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 230px\"|Party\n! valign=top style=\"width: 30px\"|Previous council\n! valign=top style=\"width: 30px\"|New council\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| 13\n| 20\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| 21\n| 17\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n| 13\n| 12\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Independent (politician)}}\n| 3\n| 2\n|-\n{{Party name with colour|Independent Liberal Democrat}}\n| 1\n| 0\n|-\n! colspan=2| Total\n! style=\"text-align: center\"| 51\n! colspan=3| 51\n|}\n\n==Ward results==\n===Brighouse ward===\n{{Election box begin |title= Brighouse}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n   |candidate  = '''Ann Martin'''\n   |votes      = 1,329\n   |percentage = 47.1\n   |change     = +25.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n   |candidate  = Howard Blagbrough\n   |votes      = 1,195\n   |percentage = 42.3\n   |change     = +2.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n   |candidate  = [[Jennie Rigg]]\n   |votes      = 273\n   |percentage = 9.8\n   |change     = &minus;28.0\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n   |votes      = 134\n   |percentage = 4.7\n   |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n   |votes      = 2,822\n   |percentage = 32.7\n   |change     = &minus;6.4\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n  |winner     = Labour Party (UK)\n  |loser = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nThe incumbent was Howard Blagbrough for the Conservative Party.\n\n===Calder ward===\n{{Election box begin |title= Calder}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n   |candidate  = '''Janet Battye'''\n   |votes      = 1,599\n   |percentage = 39.1\n   |change     = +7.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n   |candidate  = Susan Press\n   |votes      = 1,454\n   |percentage = 35.5\n   |change     = +4.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n   |candidate  = Kate Sweeny\n   |votes      = 541\n   |percentage = 13.2\n   |change     = &minus;10.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n   |candidate  = Gail Lund\n   |votes      = 477\n   |percentage = 11.7\n   |change     = &minus;1.4\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n   |votes      = 145\n   |percentage = 3.5\n   |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n   |votes      = 4,093\n   |percentage = 44.9\n   |change     = +3.4\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n  |winner     = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n  |swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nThe incumbent was Janet Battye for the Liberal Democrats.\n\n===Elland ward===\n{{Election box begin |title= Elland}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n   |candidate  = '''Pat Allen'''\n   |votes      = 950\n   |percentage = 36.4\n   |change     = &minus;7.6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n   |candidate  = Angi Gallagher\n   |votes      = 829\n   |percentage = 31.8\n   |change     = +20.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n   |candidate  = Mike Payne\n   |votes      = 595\n   |percentage = 22.8\n   |change     = &minus;6.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n   |party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n   |candidate  = Susan Thomas\n   |votes      = 225\n   |percentage = 8.6\n   |change  